[[File:MDillardAccusedOfTakingTheLastName.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard tries explaining her hiding her name]]
Johnson claimed that she had opened a shop in Harlem, as she had wanted to be home, and as she was noting that as [[Cottonmouth]] was dead, Dillard had interrupted by questioning if she thought that since Cottonmouth was the last of the [[Stokes Crime Family]], then the curse of their family would end, claiming that she made that same mistake herself. Dillard then claimed that she once believed that, with the last man to hold the name Stokes dead, then only the name Dillard would remain, and all would be right in the world, only for Johnson to claim that her mother was the only one obsessed with the name Dillard.
[[File:MDillardOnTheHerSkinColor&HerName.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard rejecting [[Tilda Johnson]]'s reasonings]]
Dillard claimed that the name was merely a fantasy, insisting that the name of Stokes was real, calling their blood a burden. Dillard went on to note that a lot more people had to die in order to make their family what it was, which Johnson scoffed at, as she claimed that it was the Dillards who were light-skinned and with good hair, while the Stokes were dark like mud, while also calling them violent and complicated. When Johnson suggested that this was why Dillard had always hated herself, Dillard laughed out loud, questioning if Johnson believed she simply hated the Stokes' name because of the color of their skin.
[[File:MDillardTellsTildaWasHerDeepShame.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard offering her views on [[Tilda Johnson]]]]
While Dillard claimed she did not know what she was talking about, Johnson had noted that she knew that Dillard had always viewed her as a disappointment and she had always tried to keep her away, only for Dillard to claim that Johnson had always brought her joy, as well as her deepest shame. The emotional Johnson had then questioned if this was because she was never a doctor like her [[Jackson Dillard|father]] had been, or because she had not inherited his light skin and green eyes, only for Dillard to explain that [[Jackson Dillard]] was never Johnson's father, explaining that Jackson had been a gay man who she had loved.
[[File:MDillardTellsTheTruthAboutJackson.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard tells the truth about [[Jackson Dillard]]]]
Dillard went on to explain to Johnson how Jackson's family had been rich, and were so pleased that he was not gay, that they had chosen to overlook him marrying a black woman, also noted that they did not care that Dillard already had a child, determined to make any lie work to cover up their son's true homosexuality. Johnson had then begun to question if Dillard really met him while at [[Howard University]], and if he was really killed by {{WPS|Contras}}, while in [[Nicaragua]], only for Dillard to insist that all this had been the truth, promising that she always loved him, which was why she kept the name of Dillard after his death.
[[File:MDillardTalksAboutLCage&CottonmouthConflict.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard blames [[Luke Cage]] for starting things]]
Dillard claimed that these lies had simply allowed Johnson to have a good father and a role model to look up to, only for Johnson to claim that [[Luke Cage]] was correct, that Dillard could not be trusted. Dillard claimed to be a survivor, only for Johnson to question if that was the reason she had murdered Cottonmouth, with Dillard then questioning if Cage had told her this, only for Johnson to ask if this was the truth. Briefly considering her next answer, Dillard told Johnson that it was indeed the truth, claiming that it was because of Cage that this had happened, as Cage's actions caused Cottonmouth to lose control
[[File:MDillardTalksAboutAbuseFromPete.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard speaks of her abuse from [[Pistol Pete]]]]
Johnson then insisted that Cage had nothing to do with Dillard killing Cottonmouth, questioning why she would do that, until Dillard finally confessed that it was because Cottonmouth loved [[Pistol Pete]] more than he loved her. Dillard then began discussing Pete, explaining for Johnson about his charisma, noting how Pete was the only one who told her she was beautiful, while all children at school would call her Black Mariah, and would also remind her how smart she was. Dillard told Johnson that she had loved Pete, until he began sneaking in her bedroom and sexually assaulting her, which she never wanted.
[[File:MDillardAdmitsToTildaOnKillingCornell.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard admits to having killed [[Cottonmouth]]]]
Dillard commented on [[Mama Mabel]]'s saying of "Family First," noting that as soon as Mabel had found out that Dillard was pregnant with Pete's baby, she had insisted that she not have an abortion, and they instead had Johnson sent over to [[Mamie Johnson]] to be raised by her instead. Dillard explained that she was already engaged to Jackson when Cottonmouth [[Assassination of Pistol Pete|executed]] Pete, and Johnson was three years old when Mabel had her first stroke, allowing Dillard to see her daughter again. Dillard then recalled how, while they had been inside [[Harlem's Paradise]], Cottonmouth had taunted her about being raped by Pete.
[[File:MDillard-INeverWantedYou.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard telling Johnson she never loved her]]
Dillard then detailed how she had struck Cottonmouth over the head with her bottle, pushed him out of the window, before [[Murder of Cottonmouth|beating him]] to death with the mic stand, for taunting her about all of that abuse she had suffered. Dillard insisted that she had never wanted all the abuse from Pete, before telling Johnson that she had never wanted to have her either, ignoring all Johnson's tears. Dillard confessed to Johnson that, although she tried to love her, she was always reminded of Pete and could not love her. As Johnson broke down into tears, she called Dillard a monster, only for Dillard to walk away from her daughter.{{Ref|LC209}}

====[[Attack on Rand Enterprises Research Facility|Attack on Rand Enterprises]]====
[[File:CageDillardKnight-SavoringTheMoment.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard signing the lease of her immunity]]
{{Quote|After all she's done, all the pain she's caused, the misery, the death. Why shouldn't I throw her through that window and give [[Bushmaster]] exactly what he wants? Tell me, Mariah, what would you do if the roles were reversed?"<br>"I would have thrown your ass to those dogs the minute they started barking.|[[Luke Cage]] and Mariah Dillard|For Pete's Sake}}
Returning to the main entrance, Dillard met with [[Luke Cage]] and [[Misty Knight]], who presented Dillard with the deal that she had requested, which would grant her full immunity from the illegal sales of her [[Hammer Industries]] guns. As Dillard looked over the documents, Knight pushed her to sign it, to which Dillard claimed that she wanted to savor the moment, noting that thanks to Cage, she was now going to become a free woman, as Dillard signed the document and handed it back to Knight.
[[File:MDillardKnowsTheStylersAreComing.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard seeing the [[Stylers]] arrive and prepare]]
Dillard watched on as Knight contacted [[Priscilla Ridley]], who proceeded to storm [[Harlem's Paradise]] with her team, only for them to discover that [[Bushmaster]] had already disappeared. When Dillard questioned what had happened, Cage noted that Bushmaster must have known that they were coming, before [[James Lucas]] implored them all to look outside, as they witnessed Bushmaster's cars driving up to the [[Rand Enterprises Research Facility]], blocking off their exits. Witnessing this, Dillard then ran back through the hallways to find somewhere to hide, while Bushmaster and his people prepared to attack the Facility.
[[File:MDillard-ThrowYouBeforeTheyBarking.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard states she would give up [[Luke Cage]]]]
Bushmaster began calling out for Cage, advising him to leave Dillard unprotected, in exchange for Bushmaster allowing him and his allies to go free, as Bushmaster called Dillard the devil that had been made flesh. Dillard began pacing up and down the hallways, unsure if Cage would allow Bushmaster to kill her to ensure the safety of his allies, with Cage even noting to Knight and Lucas that he was willing to at least consider this, due to all of the pain and misery that Dillard had caused, while Cage turned to Dillard and questioned what she would do, with Dillard admitted she would have thrown Cage to the dogs.
[[File:MDillardShootingAtOneOfTheStylers.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard stealing one of the [[Stylers]]' [[Hammer Industries Shotgun|shotgun]]s]]
Despite all this, Cage admitted that he would not do the same, noting that he had been raised better than that. Cage then stepped away, as Knight then led Dillard, Lucas, and [[Tilda Johnson]] through the facilities hallways, before Bushmaster called out that Cage's time had run out, as he sent the [[Stylers]] into the facility. While Cage leaped out a window and began fighting against Bushmaster, Knight had blocked the door to the room they were hiding in, just before Stylers arrived and began shooting at them, forcing Dillard to take cover, as Knight shot back at them before they got in, forcing Knight to fight against the Stylers.
[[File:MDillard-KissMyBlackA.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard mercilessly shooting at the [[Stylers]]]]
However, Dillard had then noticed that Knight had managed to knock a [[Hammer Industries Shotgun|shotgun]] out of one of the Stylers' hands before Dillard was able to crawl to the gun and used it to shoot and kill one of the Stylers, while another managed to get behind cover while Dillard shot back at him. While she looked around the room, Dillard locked eyes with Johnson, indicating to her to run away, while Dillard continued to hunt down all of her attackers. As Dillard marched through the hallway, shooting at the Stylers who came into view, she had muttered to them to kiss her black ass, while she still continued to shoot at all of her enemies.
[[File:MDillardReunitesWithShades-LC209.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard being finally reunited with [[Shades]]]]
As their fighting continued, Dillard had managed to make her escape from the facility, as she began walking back into [[Harlem]], while armed with her shotgun, leaving Cage to then defeat Bushmaster in combat, resulting with Bushmaster being arrested by the [[New York City Police Department]]. However, while Dillard was walking across a bridge, she noticed that a car was seemingly following her, as she waited for the car to stop before turning around and aiming up the shotgun, only for her to realize that it was actually [[Shades]], as she commented that she had known that Shades would find her, as he said he had got her.
[[File:ShadesDillardCaptureAnasi.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard witnesses the now kidnapped [[Anansi]]]]
Dillard then told Shades that she was done playing by their rules and denying whom she really was, while also insisting that she now knew who she actually was, and wanted to claim everything that was hers. With that, Shades then passionately kissed Dillard, before telling her that he had something to give to her. Shades had then opened up the trunk of his car, revealing to Dillard that he had successfully managed to capture Bushmaster's uncle, [[Anansi]], as he had just left him tied up inside the trunk, with Dillard and Shades then reciting [[Mama Mabel]]'s saying of "Family First," before then closing the trunk on Anansi.{{Ref|LC209}}

===Regaining Power===
====Returning to the Paradise====
[[File:MDillardArrivesBackInHarlemsParadise.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard arriving back into [[Harlem's Paradise]]]]
{{Quote|Call everyone home, it's good to have the money, but we need the streets back. I want [[Bushmaster]]'s head on a goddamn platter."<br>"We just have to find him."<br>"Oh, we have help on that front.|Mariah Dillard and [[Shades]]|The Main Ingredient}}
In the wake of her escape, Dillard returned into [[Harlem's Paradise]], as she found the remains from all of [[Bushmaster]]'s experiments with the [[Nightshade]], as Dillard insisted someone would have to clean it up. Dillard then turned to [[Benjamin Donovan]] and claimed that the entire situation was his fault, to which Donovan had insisted that he had called her to rectify the situation, although Dillard claimed that Donovan was only there before his deal with Bushmaster fell through.
[[File:MDillardIsInformedHerMoneyBeingBack.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard learning that her money has return]]
Donovan had then informed Dillard that he had been able to reclaim all of her holdings, cash, as well as Harlem's Paradise, as Dillard then checked her bank records on her phone to confirm that this was true. When [[Shades]] questioned how this was possible, Donovan had then explained that since [[Piranha Jones]] had been tortured by Bushmaster when the transfer of the funds was made, it was illegal. While Dillard began kicking over Bushmaster's candles, Shades asked about their issues with the [[New York City Police Department]], although Donovan remained confident that this would not be any problem for them.
[[File:BenDonovanThreatenedByMDillard.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard closely threatens [[Benjamin Donovan]]]]
Dillard listened as Donovan explained that he could tie up the police in a legal case for years and they would still lose, while Dillard could keep all of her money and assets. Donovan questioned if all his work settled any disagreements between them, to which Dillard responded by grabbing a tight hold of Donovan's testicles while insisting that it was not even close to getting settled. Dillard questioned if Donovan had ever stolen money from her, which he denied, as Dillard finally let go of his testicles. Once Donovan went to leave the club, Dillard then made a mocking comment about Donovan's nickname of Big Ben.
[[File:ShadesDillardRetakeParadise.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard and [[Shades]] making their next plans]]
Once they were alone, Dillard told Shades to call back everyone from the [[Stokes Crime Family]], noting that while it was good to have their money back from the [[Stylers]], they still needed to reclaim their control over [[Harlem]]'s streets. Dillard had then told Shades how she wanted to see Bushmaster's head on a platter, to which Shades simply noted they needed to find him first, since Bushmaster had already escaped from the police's custody, although Dillard then noted that they now had [[Anansi]] who could help them to find where Bushmaster would be hiding, much to the delight of Shades as they embraced each other.
[[File:ShadesHandsOverRevolver.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard is given back her [[Stokes' Revolver|pistol]] from [[Shades]]]]
Dillard took back her usual position on Harlem's Paradise's balcony, as she was rejoined by Shades. Dillard then explained that she was thinking about [[Mama Mabel]] and [[Cottonmouth]], as well as everyone else who had stood in that spot, while she claimed that Harlem was ruled from that balcony, noting that this could feel like she was ruling the world from there. Shades then presented Dillard with the [[Stokes' Revolver]], which had been found in the ruins of her [[Mariah Dillard's Brownstone|Brownstone]], with Shades noting that he had not given it to her before this, as he was unsure if he could still trust her, as Dillard took the gun from him.{{Ref|LC210}}

====Cage and Rand's Threat====
[[File:MDillardGreetingAnansi-LC210.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard greeting [[Anansi]] after his kidnapping]]
{{Quote|You can tear shit up if you want to, it's just gonna waste time. You better find [[Bushmaster]] before I do."<br>"Don't do anything stupid, Mariah. Or actually, please, do something stupid, so I can take this whole thing down."<br>"Do your best.|Mariah Dillard and [[Luke Cage]]|The Main Ingredient}}
Dillard then stepped back into her office, as she scoffed at a portrait of {{WPS|Marcus Garvey}} that [[Bushmaster]] had hung up on the wall. Having poured herself a drink, and sat at her desk, Dillard watched as [[Shades]] and [[Sugar]] brought in [[Anansi]], with Dillard mockingly greeting him with the traditional [[Jamaica]]n greeting, while Anansi remained silent and stared at Dillard. When Dillard insisted that he did not scare her, Anansi scoffed and claimed that she was consumed with fear.
[[File:MDillard-LukeCageDannyRandAreHere.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard sees [[Luke Cage]] and [[Iron Fist]] arrive]]
However, before Dillard could continue interrogating Anansi, she was interrupted as Shades said that [[Luke Cage]] and [[Danny Rand]] had just arrived into [[Harlem's Paradise]]. Stepping to her office window, Dillard looked down at Cage and Rand, before then telling Shades that she would go out to speak with them personally. As Shades questioned why she would do this, Dillard had explained that it would be the only way for her to prevent them from coming upstairs and discovering a captured Anansi. Greeting them, Dillard told Cage and Rand that the club would not be opened until the next week due to cleaning.
[[File:ShadesDillardThreatenCageRand.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard greeting [[Luke Cage]] and [[Danny Rand]]]]
Cage informed Dillard that they were looking for [[Bushmaster]], only for Dillard to then claim that she had moved on from the situation, which Cage doubted was the truth. Cage had reminded Dillard that she had already walked away from [[Misty Knight]]'s immunity deal, while telling her not to tear up their streets, only for Dillard to warn that she would attack anyone who came after her family. In response, Cage had then questioned where [[Tilda Johnson]] was, with Dillard explaining that she did not know, while Cage had questioned if she had even bothered to go into [[Mother's Touch]] to see if Johnson was safe from danger.
[[File:MDillardTalksBackToLCage-LC210.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard being insulted by [[Luke Cage]]'s threat]]
Dillard told Cage that Johnson had just gone her own way, calling it the curse of parenthood, before questioning how [[James Lucas]] was doing, noting how Lucas seemed to be more fun than Cage. Dillard then offered Rand a drink, which he politely refused, before she told Cage that he could tear up [[Harlem]], but it would only waste time and warned him that he should find Bushmaster. When Cage told Dillard to not do anything stupid, he immediately took it back, telling her to do something stupid so that he could bring down their [[Stokes Crime Family]], although Dillard was unintimidated as they walked out.{{Ref|LC210}}

====Interrogating Anansi====
[[File:MDillardColdlyThreatsTheCaptiveAnansi.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard goes back to interrogating [[Anansi]]]]
{{Quote|Buggy could only fight for one family, and he chose the right one. He should have finished off the whole raasclaat McIver family when he had the chance... What? You think this is funny?"<br>"Mi laugh at mi own folly. When Johnny declared war on yuh, mi felt sorry for yuh. Mi nah want him to destroy you the way the Stokes destroyed him own family.|Mariah Dillard and [[Anansi]]|The Main Ingredient}}
Once [[Luke Cage]] and [[Danny Rand]] had left, Dillard then returned into her office, as she expressed surprise that [[Anansi]] did not even attempt to alert Cage and Rand to his situation, to which Anansi claimed that his fate was already sealed so it would not matter either way, noting that Dillard's fate was also sealed. However, Anansi had then also claimed that there was nothing that Dillard could do to him that would make him betray [[Bushmaster]], although Dillard had then coldly told Anansi not to be so sure about that.
[[File:MDillardArguesWithAnansi-1.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard arguing about the [[Harlem's Paradise|club]]'s ownership]]
Dillard instructed [[Shades]] to untie Anansi, noting that if he was going to attempt to escape, he would have done it already, noting that if he did try and run then Shades would have to shoot him. Dillard offered Anansi some [[Bushmaster Rum]], which he refused, while Dillard went on to note that she understood what [[Buggy Stokes]] meant as it was the smoothest rum she had. While Anansi warned that Dillard should enjoy it before her judgement, Dillard warned that she had more time than he did. Dillard then commented that she had lied to Bushmaster about how Buggy had stolen [[Quincy McIver]]'s formula for the rum.
[[File:MDillardArguesWithAnansi-2.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard threatening to kill the McIver family]]
Dillard went on to note that she recalled [[Mama Mabel]] telling stories about Buggy and Quincy's dreams of success, commenting on how their [[Stokes Crime Family]] had fought hard for [[Harlem's Paradise]] to succeed over the years, although Anansi called Buggy a slave, which angered Dillard. As Anansi continued to insult Dillard, calling her lazy and fighting for the scraps, Shades took out his gun to threaten him, while Dillard commented on how [[Jamaica]] did not even become free until [[1962]], as they continued to argue about the conflict between the two families, noting that they should have murdered every McIver.
[[File:ShadesDillardThreatenAnansi.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard asking [[Anansi]] where [[Bushmaster]] is]]
As Anansi laughed, Dillard questioned if he thought that the situation was funny, to which Anansi claimed that he was laughing at himself, noting that when Bushmaster began their [[War for Harlem]], he had felt sorry for her. However, Anansi then explained that he could see that Dillard had the same darkness which Bushmaster had, claiming that she deserved her punishment. Dillard questioned where Bushmaster was, only for Anansi to claim that he did not know, and would not tell her if he did. When Anansi had noted that those seeking revenge had to dig two graves, Dillard claimed that it would not be enough.{{Ref|LC210}}

====[[Massacre at Gwen's|Massacre at ''Gwen's'']]====
[[File:ShadesDillardWalkToGwens.png|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard and [[Shades]] walking towards [[Gwen's]]]]
{{Quote|Billie, it was you. That's how he knew about [[Piranha Jones|Piranha]]. That's how he knew how to get to me. And where."<br>"Ms. Dillard, please."<br>"The name is Stokes. Mariah Stokes.|Mariah Stokes and [[Stephanie Miller]]|The Main Ingredient}}
Dillard and [[Shades]] then took their captured [[Anansi]] down the streets of [[Harlem]], as Shades was informed that a [[Stylers' Grow House]] had just been burnt down to the ground, likely due to the vigilante actions of [[Luke Cage]] and [[Danny Rand]]. Upon hearing this, Dillard noted that Cage and Rand were doing their dirty work for them, and it would be a perfect time for them to finally strike back against [[Bushmaster]], as Shades assumed she meant to send his family an ultimatum in order to end their conflict against Bushmaster once and for all.
[[File:MDillardDiscoversSMillerBetrayal.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Dillard discovers [[Stephanie Miller]]'s betrayal]]
Arriving at ''Gwen's'', one of Dillard's henchmen shot out the cameras before Dillard and Shades stepped inside, with guns aimed at all of the terrified customers inside the restaurant. Dillard had then looked around their restaurant, watching as one of her men knocking [[Ingrid Mackintosh]] to the floor while Anansi was dragged inside. However, Dillard then noticed that [[Stephanie Miller]] was there, as she begged Dillard not to harm anyone. Dillard then realized that it was Miller who betrayed her, allowing Bushmaster to learn about [[Piranha Jones]] and how to target her, while Miller had then begged Dillard for mercy.
[[File:MDillardOrdersTheMassacreAtGwens.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes orders to kill all the people in [[Gwen's]]]]
As Miller had begged Dillard for mercy, Dillard stated that her name was Mariah Stokes, not Dillard. She then ordered one of her men to shoot Miller in the head, resulting with another customer running in fear, as they were then also shot and killed, along with every other innocent bystander inside of the restaurant. Once everyone was dead, Stokes had Anansi's blindfold removed, so that he could look at the corpses surrounding him. As a devastated Anansi crawled across the floor in despair, the shocked Shades stepped over to Stokes and noted that this was not what they had discussed, which Stokes dismissed.
[[File:ShadesDillard-BurningAnansi.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes drops the match to burn [[Anansi]] alive]]
Stokes then had Anansi dragged before her, while her men grabbed some of the [[Bushmaster Rum]], while Stokes noted that it was time for them to see if Bushmaster was right about the power of fire. Stokes watched as her men poured the rum over Anansi, who then furiously warned that he would continue to haunt Stokes for the rest of her life. However, Stokes stopped Anansi's ranting by setting fire to the rum, causing Anansi to burst into flames. As Anansi continued screaming in agony, Stokes then drew the [[Stokes' Revolver]], and shot him in the head, as Stokes noted that Bushmaster would come for them now.
[[File:MDillardWinsBackHarlemsParadise.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes throws a party at [[Harlem's Paradise]]]]
Confident in her victory, Stokes returned to [[Harlem's Paradise]], where she watched as [[Faith Evans]] and [[Jadakiss]] performed together. Stokes then [[Cottonmouth]]'s portrait of {{WPS|Biggie Smalls}} put back on the wall of her office, replacing a portrait of {{WPS|Marcus Garvey}}, which was hung by Bushmaster. Taking her usual positioning on the balcony of Harlem's Paradise, Stokes watched Evans and Jadakiss' performance on their stage, as she was brought champagne by some of her henchmen and delighted in her victory over Bushmaster. However, Stokes failed to see Shades walking away, disheartened by her violent action.{{Ref|LC210}}

====Upgraded Protections====
[[File:DillardFollowingAlexToASecretDoor.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes follows [[Alex Wesley]] to the saferoom]]
{{Quote|You think that this plastic bullshit is going to prevent that man from coming to get you after what you did last night?"<br>"What we did... When the time is right, we will pop him in his bumboclaat ass once and for all. We're building this safe room for a reason, Hernan. Bushmaster's coming.|[[Shades]] and Mariah Stokes|The Creator}}
With the threat of [[Bushmaster]]'s revenge still strong, Stokes was given a tour of all the new security measures in [[Harlem's Paradise]], as [[Alex Wesley]] showed her their new panic room under the club, as Stokes delighted over the new hand scanner, which Wesley explained was gifted by [[Atreus Plastics]]. Once inside, Wesley then told Stokes about his idea to hang up her {{WPS|Jean-Michel Basquiat}} painting while reassuring Stokes that the bunker was strong enough to protect her.
[[File:DillardPromisesToKillBushmaster-LC211.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes promises to kill [[Bushmaster]] for good]]
However, as Stokes delighted in Wesley's promises, [[Shades]] scoffed at their designs, questioning if Stokes really believed that the bunker would actually be strong enough to protect them all, in the wake of the [[Massacre at Gwen's|Massacre]] at [[Gwen's]], since he had known that nothing would to able to keep Bushmaster from getting his revenge. However, Stokes reminded Shades of his part in the massacre, noting that they would soon [[Infiltration into Harlem's Paradise|kill]] Bushmaster once and for all, making it clear that they were building their safe house for a reason, as she knew that Bushmaster was coming for her, and they simply needed to be ready for him.{{Ref|LC211}}

====Hunt for Ingrid Mackintosh====
[[File:DillardWatchingWJBP-TVNewsReport.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes watching the [[WJBP-TV]] news reports]]
{{Quote|We're gonna make big moves, man, you and I, just like we talked about, but in order for that to happen I need you to leave Hernan behind, just for a while, and be my Shades."<br>"You think you can just wash your hands of all this? You think it's that simple?"<br>"I do. I need you to do what Shades always does.|Mariah Stokes and [[Shades]]|The Creator}}
However, when Stokes watched the [[WJBP-TV]] news report, she had then discovered that [[Karen Page]] was reporting a survivor from their [[Massacre at Gwen's]], although [[Misty Knight]] and [[Priscilla Ridley]] had failed to confirm if it was actually true. While Stokes had watched the news reports, she was then rejoined by [[Shades]], as she had informed him of the survivor from the massacre, who she had learned was [[Ingrid Mackintosh]], the wife of [[Anansi]], with Stokes ordering Shades to locate Mackintosh and execute her.
[[File:DillardJustifiesTheMassacreToShades.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes discusses her next orders to [[Shades]]]]
Despite this, Shades tried to reassure Stokes that, if Mackintosh had actually survived the massacre, there would be little chance that she would want to talk to the [[New York City Police Department]] about the experience. Shades sat down as he demanded to know what Stokes had been thinking by ordering the massacre, to which Stokes insisted that it was due to [[Bushmaster]] starting the [[War for Harlem]], while she insisted that she did not start the conflict. Stokes had then informed Shades that [[Alex Wesley]] had already sent [[Ricky]] and [[Tony (New York)|Tony]] to search for Mackintosh, telling Shades to go and join them with the search.
[[File:DillardOrderingToKillIngrid.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes tells [[Shades]] to kill [[Ingrid Mackintosh]]]]
However, Shades only laughed, as he questioned if Stokes had given Wesley the power to give orders to the [[Stokes Crime Family]], only for Stokes to mock Shades for being insecure about Wesley role. Stokes then claimed to be able to see the fear and conflict in Shades' eyes, noting that she used to have the same look, insisting that they would still be able to make big moves in [[Harlem]], but claimed that for this to happen, Shades needed to be her true gangster again, which would allow her to wash her hands of their violence, as she told him to take care of Mackintosh so that she could then secure their future.{{Ref|LC211}}

====Deal with Hai-Qing Yang====
[[File:DillardHQYang-HarlemsParadiseMeeting.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes holds a meeting with [[Hai-Qing Yang]]]]
{{Quote|Guns are great, they maintain the peace, but heroin, everybody's on it now. That's true currency."<br>"I couldn't agree with you more, but that's our business."<br>"And no one wants to stop that... If we can come to our satisfactory agreement, I'm willing to allow the [[Yangsi Gonshi]] to run China White through [[Harlem]].|Mariah Stokes and [[Hai-Qing Yang]]|The Creator}}
Intending to increase her power over [[Harlem]], Stokes invited [[Hai-Qing Yang]] to meet her in [[Harlem's Paradise]], to discuss her being involved with his heroin business, as Yang had first questioned why she would want to get involved, as their [[Stokes Crime Family]] had previously only been focused on their gun businesses. Stokes explained to Yang that, while guns maintained the peace, heroin was where the money was, although Yang insisted that the [[Yangsi Gonshi]] were not looking for to get any more competition.
[[File:Dillard-HQYangMeeting-CU.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes and [[Hai-Qing Yang]] discuss a unity]]
Stokes insisted that she would not stop Yang's organizations, as she claimed that if they came to an arrangement, she would be willing to allow the Yangsi Gonshi to run all their [[Chinatown]] based operations through Harlem, which would allow for greater profits for the Yangsi Gonshi. In response to her propositions, Yang had then noted that he had heard that Stokes had half a billion dollars to her name, so clearly she did not actually need to be involved in the heroin business, while he noted that he remembered how [[Mama Mabel]] was always against the idea of the Stokes family being involved in the heroin business.
[[File:Dillard-ShakingHQYangsHand.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes finishes dealings with [[Hai-Qing Yang]]]]
Stokes had insisted to Yang that now that Mabel and the rest of those Stokes' were dead, and now she was running the businesses. Stokes told Yang that she was now thinking bigger than any of her previous family members ever had before, telling him that it was time for them to let the ghosts of the past die, so they could join forces at long last, to their mutual benefit. With that, Stokes offered her hand to Yang and suggested that they tear down the metaphorical wall that was put up between their organizations, when Yang stood up and shook Stokes' hand, agreeing to work with her, much to Stokes' satisfaction.{{Ref|LC211}}

====Ghosts of the Past====
[[File:BlackMariahMamaMabel-YouDead.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes imagines [[Mama Mabel]] in front of her]]
{{Quote|I legitimized our name, I built community centers and real estate projects, safe spaces for women and kids, every time something connected to you came up to taint it. All this is your fault."<br>"Even [[Murder of Cottonmouth|killing]] sweet [[Cornell Stokes|Cornell]]?"<br>"He wasn't sweet anymore, after what you did to him.|Mariah Stokes and [[Mama Mabel]]|The Creator}}
Following her deal with [[Hai-Qing Yang]], Stokes had remained in her office inside [[Harlem's Paradise]], where she made herself a drink to celebrate their deals. However, Stokes then began to imagine [[Mama Mabel]] was also in the room, as she insisted that she was better than Mabel ever was, which Mabel mocked, claiming that drugs were their plague. However, Stokes simply insisted that she no longer had to listen to Mabel, who had already been dead for several years.
[[File:BlackMariahListsHerAccomplishments.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes justifying her actions to [[Mama Mabel]]]]
Mabel had then accused Stokes of dragging the [[Stokes Crime Family]] through the streets, although Stokes insisted that she had legitimized their own name by building the [[Crispus Attucks Complex]] and [[Shirley Chisholm Complex]], which had aimed to be a safe space for women and children who were living in [[Harlem]], while claiming that every time she tried to build something good, the legacy of Mabel came back to taint it. When Stokes claimed that everything was her fault, Mabel had questioned if this had included her murdering [[Cottonmouth]], although Stokes insisted that Mabel had turned a sweet boy into a murderer.
[[File:BlackMariahShoutsAtPete-Imagination.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes yells at the [[Pistol Pete]] hallucination]]
While Stokes continued to argue with Mabel, she also imagined [[Pistol Pete]] in the office, who told Mabel to lay off Stokes, claiming that she was doing her best. Stokes began backing away, while she imagined Pete telling her that they agreed about joining the drug game, calling Stokes smart, tough, and beautiful, claiming that he had molded her to be that way. Pete had told Stokes that he forgave her for ordering Cottonmouth to murder him, although Mabel insisted that this had been her. When Pete had referenced [[Tilda Johnson]] following in their footsteps, Stokes furiously ordered him to never say her name.
[[File:BlackMariahRealizesSheWasImagining.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes realizes she is going mentally insane]]
While Pete continued discussing his legacy on Johnson's personality, saying that she had become even more ambitious than both of them had ever been, and that it was meant to be, Stokes furiously insisted that her uncle should not also be her father, while Mabel commented that Stokes was clearly working out some past trauma. Attempting to regain control over her own mind, Stokes told Mabel and Pete that it was now her world, insisting that she was owed more and she would eventually own all [[New York City]]. With that, Stokes turned around, as she saw that her visions of Mabel and Pete had now vanished.{{Ref|LC211}}

====Confronted by Shades====
[[File:AlexDillardNoticingShadesWalkingIn.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes and [[Alex Wesley]] stopped by [[Shades]]]]
{{Quote|But the dead are dead, are you a vegan now? You've been a god damn carnivore the whole time I've known you, a predator I loved that. Did you kill the [[Ingrid Mackintosh|bitch]] or what?"<br>"I'm done."<br>"She could go to the cops, Hernan. If I go down, you go down. Your ass was right next to me the whole time, firing.|Mariah Stokes and [[Shades]]|The Creator}}
Stokes had continued drinking, as she was joined by [[Alex Wesley]] and invited him to rejoin her for a drink. Once they had both gotten quite drunk and shared a laugh, Wesley indicated that he should leave, while Stokes insisted that Wesley was to call her by her first name. However, they were then interrupted by [[Shades]], who had found Stokes almost on top of Wesley, whom she had claimed had always been loyal to her and said that he was always there when she needed him, only for Shades to order Wesley to leave.
[[File:DillardOnMurderingOthers-RulesBroken.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes listening to [[Shades]] about their rules]]
Although Stokes insisted that only she could tell Wesley to leave, he had then run out the door, once Shades had pulled out a gun. Once they were alone, Stokes accused Shades of being jealous of her and Wesley, which he denied, while he claimed that he was seeing Stokes for the first time again. As Stokes poured herself a drink, Shades then told her that there was a code on the streets, and actual rules to the crimes they committed, claiming that their [[Massacre at Gwen's|massacre]] at [[Gwen's]] had broken those rules, only for Stokes to remind Shades about [[Candace Miller]], and how she was innocent but he had killed her regardless.
[[File:Dillard-AreYouAVeganNow.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes criticizes [[Shades]] for his new doubts]]
However, Shades insisted that Miller was guilty as soon as she took their money, and broke their rules by talking to [[Misty Knight]], noting that he had also killed her to protect Stokes, although Stokes simply dismissed this. Stokes had then mockingly questioned if Shades was becoming vegan, claiming that Shades had been her predator, for as long as she had known him, before questioning if he had killed [[Ingrid Mackintosh]]. However, instead of answering, Shades told Stokes that he was done, with Stokes reminding him that Mackintosh could go to the [[New York City Police Department]] and take them both down.
[[File:Dillard-BushmasterStartedTheWar.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes justifies the reason for the [[Massacre at Gwen's|massacre]]]]
Stokes reminded Shades of how he had also been shooting during their massacre, only for Shades to remind her that he had told her to use [[Anansi]] as leverage against [[Bushmaster]], and she did not have to kill innocent people, although Stokes argued that Shades had always known what would happen at Gwen's, which was why he scouted it. When Stokes then insisted that Bushmaster had started the [[War for Harlem]], and she was ending it, Shades told her that she had lost her heart, noting that he had looked at her face while Anansi was burning alive, and she had never even blinked while he was screaming.
[[File:ShadesBeingSeduced-S2E11.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes attempting to seduce [[Shades]] again]]
In response, Stokes had then claimed that she was done babysitting, and reminded Shades of how he had told her that her first kill would always be her hardest, before it got easier, insisting that he had been correct about this. Stokes reminding Shades of how he had protected her after she murdered [[Cottonmouth]], as she caressed Shades' body and noted how scared she had been that night, until he had arrived. However, as Stokes had claimed that Shades had made her into who she was now, Shades took her hands away and accused her of being a crazy bitch, before then attempting to walk out of her office.
[[File:DillardInsultsShades&Comanche.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes insults [[Comanche]] in front of [[Shades]]]]
Annoyed at him walking away, Stokes then claimed that Shades had been different ever since [[Comanche]] had died, while noting that she had recognized the looks of jealousy that Comanche had given her, making it clear that she knew Shades and Comanche were lovers as they were inside [[Seagate Penitentiary]]. Stokes went on to question if Shades had actually loved Comanche, before noting how she wished that she had been the one to pull that trigger on Comanche, noting that she would have shot him twice into the gut, so that he would die slowly and painfully, while she would have made Shades watch.
[[File:ShadesStranglesDillard.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes being strangled to death by [[Shades]]]]
However, these comments about the death of Comanche had only resulted in Stokes enraging Shades, who grabbed her by her throat and furiously threw her down onto her desk, attempting to chock the life out of Stokes, while she desperately attempted to kick him off of her, only to find herself unable to get Shades off her, as she was now completely at his mercy. Despite Stokes still being unable to defend herself against him, Shades eventually let down, as Stokes coughed and regained her breath, with Shades claiming that she was not even worth the effort of killing her, while he also called Stokes pathetic.
[[File:Dillard-ILitTheMatch&PulledTheTrigger.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes admits her crimes to [[Tilda Johnson]]]]
As Stokes sat up, struggling to breathe, she demanded that Shades come back, as she was not done with him, only watch him walk out the door without another word. However, Stokes then saw that [[Tilda Johnson]] had come to [[Harlem's Paradise]], as she noted that she had believed that Johnson had left town, as Johnson demanded to know if her mother was responsible for the massacre at Gwen's. However, Stokes confidently told Johnson that she did not just give the order, but lit the match and pulled the trigger, which horrified Johnson, who said goodbye to Stokes before she also walked away from her.{{Ref|LC211}}

===Final Days===
====United Criminal Force====
[[File:UnitedNationsOfCriminals-LC.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes meeting with other criminal bosses]]
{{Quote|Plenty of customers for whatever you are offering, and increasing real estate opportunities to wash the profits."<br>"But you'll be in charge."<br>"It's my black face on the money. But it's still green.|Mariah Stokes and [[Rosalie Carbone]]|Can't Front on Me}}
In an attempt to regain her control over [[Harlem]], Stokes had arranged a meeting with various heads of the crime families of [[New York City]], as she met them at their [[Calderwood Auction House]]. Sitting behind them, Stokes greeted the criminals and thanked them for joining her, only for [[Eric Hong]] to note that the last time the [[Korean Mob]] attended one of Stokes' meetings, it resulted with his [[Peter Hong|brother]] being killed by [[Diamondback]].
[[File:BlackMariahWantsToMakeADeal-S2E12.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes states that the [[Stylers]] are defeated]]
While Dillard had insisted that Diamondback was a plague on them all, [[Anibal Izqueda]] noted that [[Bushmaster]] was their latest plague to deal with, with [[Rosalie Carbone]] noting that all of these plagues had appeared to begin with Stokes. While Stokes questioned if Carbone meant to compare her to God, Carbone had insisted that she viewed Stokes as a pebble in her shoe. Stokes insisted that the [[Stylers]] were defeated, although Hong insisted that there would be no hopes for them joining forces while Bushmaster was still alive, despite [[Hai-Qing Yang]] insisting that they now had a plan to deal with Bushmaster.
[[File:BlackMariahConvincesCrimelordsProfits.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes offers a deal to control over [[Harlem]]]]
However, Carbone questioned a need for them to join forces, noting how all of the other crime families could work their organizations as they did before, while it was only the [[Stokes Crime Family]] who were the problem, to which Stokes had then claimed that the problem with the [[Carbone Crime Family]] was that they kept themselves isolated. As Stokes continued, she insisted that they could all make bigger profits by joining forces, as she offered Harlem as the gateway to a greater deal, noting that they could use her real estate opportunities to wash their profits, with Stokes confirming that she would be in charge.
[[File:BlackMariahAllowsCrimelordToBid.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes assures open access for the bosses]]
Stokes had reassured the group that she still had legitimate access to various political assets which they could use, promising to open the walls around Harlem for specific access for their organizations. When Carbone questioned what the price would be for this, Stokes did not answer and instead admired the Auction house, calling it a cathedral to power and privilege. Stokes had then witnessed her own item, the galley of {{WPS|The Souls of Black Folk}} come up for auction, as Stokes then made it clear that she expected all of them to bid for the item, or else only the [[Yangsi Gonshi]] would be given her access into Harlem.
[[File:MDillardHQYang-LeavingAuctionHouse.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes and [[Hai-Qing Yang]] leave the auction]]
With that, Stokes and Yang left all the other criminal leaders to bid for her item, while also noting that the book would only be a placeholder, as she expected to be given it back from whoever paid for it. Stokes then met with [[Alex Wesley]], who complimented her on their meeting, while Yang noted that his security teams were under the impression that Bushmaster was still watching them closely, with Stokes noting that she hoped that this was indeed the case, as they had planned to lure Bushmaster into their trap. With that, Wesley then led Stokes out of the auction house, as they drove back to Harlem together.{{Ref|LC212}}

====Drinking with Luke Cage====
[[File:BlackMariahNoticesLCageArrives-S2E12.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes learning that [[Luke Cage]] has arrived]]
{{Quote|Of course, you're going to save me. You are my dark chocolate boy scout, it's what I love about our relationship."<br>"There is no relationship, I hate you."<br>"It's the hate that makes it great. I used to daydream about how to kill you, drown you, poison you, burn you, break your heart. So foolish, I didn't appreciate what was right in front of me.|Mariah Stokes and [[Luke Cage]]|Can't Front on Me}}
Having returned to [[Harlem's Paradise]], Stokes then heard the sudden arrival of [[Luke Cage]], as he called out to her. Despite her henchmen holding Cage at gunpoint, Stokes remained calm and invited him to come up into her office to talk. As Stokes collected two glasses of [[Bushmaster Rum]], she noted Cage's torn hoodie and suggested that she could introduce him to [[Dapper Dan]], although Cage noted that he had already met Dan, noting that [[Cottonmouth]] had actually ruined the last suit that Dan had given to him.
[[File:LCageMDillardTalkAboutYangsiGonshi.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes telling [[Luke Cage]] to drink together]]
Stokes then offered Cage a drink, which he refused, as he claimed he never drank while on duty, before he then explained that he had just managed to bring down a [[Yangsi Gonshi Warehouse]], which she had set up with [[Hai-Qing Yang]], as Cage commented that Stokes' plan to put [[Bushmaster]]'s name onto a new batch of [[Bushmaster (Heroin)|heroin]] was genius, as it had lured Bushmaster out of the shadows to shut it down, noting that it also worked when [[Arturo Rey III]] did the same thing to him, all while Stokes denied everything. Cage noted that he did not care how many allies Stokes thought she had, while he called her "Black Mariah."
[[File:BlackMariahMakesFunOfLCage-S2E12.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is insulted once again by [[Luke Cage]]]]
Cage told Stokes that Bushmaster was still coming for her, noting that the [[Stokes Crime Family]] crews would still not be able to protect her, although Stokes insisted that she had always lived her life with some opposition. When Cage had noted that he had already saved her life twice, and would not do it a third time, Stokes smirked, claiming that Cage was lying to himself. Stokes then claimed that she had learned something while [[James Lucas]] was showing her pictures of Cage as a young man, claiming that Cage was still just that goofy kid who did not know what to do with his powers, as Cage asked her opinion.
[[File:LCageBlackMariahFaceOff-S2E12.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes speaks against [[Luke Cage]]'s heroics]]
Stokes had claimed that she was already doing more than Cage, even without his powers, while insisting that Cage would still come to her rescue from Bushmaster once again, with Stokes calling Cage a boy scout. When Cage insisted that they had no relationship, as he hated her, Stokes insisted that this hatred was what made their relationship great, while she went on to explain how she used to daydream about how she would kill Cage, suggesting drowning, poisoning or burning him, as she caressed Cage's face and suggested she could break his heart, before she realized that she had been a foolish exercise.
[[File:LCageTellsMDillardThatTheRumIsGood.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes tells [[Luke Cage]] that she trusts him]]
When Stokes claimed that she had not appreciated what was right in front of her, she explained that Cage was the only man she had ever been able to rely on, as [[Harlem]] could also count on him, while Stokes called Cage a man of the people, only to then call this his weakness, noting that this was almost poetic. With that, Cage then took up the glass of rum, noting how things could change and he was no longer on duty, and therefore could drink with Stokes. Cage had then noted how good their Bushmaster rum was, before promising to pour some out once Stokes and Bushmaster's [[War for Harlem|conflict]] was finally concluded.
[[File:BlackMariahPlanningAFreeParty.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes planning for a free party at the [[Harlem's Paradise|club]]]]
With that, Cage then walked out of Harlem's Paradise, as Stokes then proceeded to get her phone and had called Maxine, telling her to get on the phone to [[KRS-One]], explaining that she intended to host a free concert in Harlem's Paradise, claiming that this would be a unity jam, noting that she now intended for their entire club to become packed. Stokes' party invite spread across Harlem, with Stokes knowing that Bushmaster would likely use this as an opportunity to attack her, and Cage would be left with no choice but to stop him in order to save all the lives of the innocent guests at the party, as well as Stokes.{{Ref|LC212}}

====[[Infiltration into Harlem's Paradise|Bushmaster's Final Attack]]====
[[File:MDillardTellsShadesToSitWithHer-S2E12.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is reunited back with [[Shades]] again]]
{{Quote|I know my goddamn rights. Do you really think this is gonna hold? It's [[Shades|his]] word against mine. And he is a goddamn gutter gangster. A lowlife. And I am Mariah Stokes. Forever councilwoman of [[Harlem]], millionaire philanthropist.|Mariah Stokes to [[Misty Knight]]|Can't Front on Me}}
As she planned, Stokes hosted a large party at [[Harlem's Paradise]], as she watched [[KRS-One]] performing on stage. During the performance, Stokes had then noticed the return of [[Shades]], who was first searched by her security teams before being allowed to come close to her. Stokes immediately ordered Shades to remove his sunglasses, as she questioned if he had been crying, to which he claimed to simply have allergies to bullshit, with Stokes then telling Shades to keep the sunglasses removed, as she had always liked looking at his eyes.
[[File:MDillard-IToldYouSo.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes tells [[Luke Cage]] that she told him so]]
Once Shades sat down, Stokes questioned what he wanted, to which Shades claimed to only want her, although Stokes noted that it was ever that simple with Shades. Taking her hands, Shades told Stokes that he was sorry, suggesting that they should talk more in her office, although Stokes had insisted that they continue to catch KRS-One's performance. While they listened to the performance, Stokes noticed that [[Luke Cage]] had arrived, as Stokes muttered that she told him so. Shades had told Stokes that they needed to talk, as she questioned if he was going to apologize for assaulting her the previous evening.
[[File:MDillardShadesStandingInClub-PurpleLight.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is asked for her [[Yangsi Gonshi]] deal]]
When Shades noted that he was not proud of how he handled their disagreement, Stokes noted that Shades was who he was, to which he questioned who she was supposed to be, noting how she made a deal with [[Hai-Qing Yang]] to join the [[Yangsi Gonshi]]'s drug trade, while Stokes suggested that he not make these accusations against her so fast, as she had not yet forgiven him. Once KRS-One had completed his performance, he gestured to Stokes, who applauded him, before telling Shades that she needed to speak to him in private, as she had invited him to come and join her in their safe room under the club.
[[File:ShadesThreatenedByDillard-Revolver.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes aims her revolver directly at [[Shades]]]]
Once they were downstairs, Stokes had led Shades to their safe room in silence, where she opened the door with a handprint scanner and poured herself a drink. Once they were alone, Shades suggested that they could still go back to the way things were between them, before kissing her. However, Stokes suspected that Shades had alternative motives for returning, as she then aimed the [[Stokes' Revolver]] at his stomach. Stokes was able to confirm her theory that Shades was the rat for the [[New York City Police Department]], as she found the hidden wire on his chest, which had been recording their conversations.
[[File:ShadesAimingGunAtBushmaster.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes being closely protected by [[Shades]]]]
As she held Shades at gunpoint, Stokes ordered him to sit down, as she noted on how he had become a snitch like [[Comanche]]. However, before Stokes could question him, Shades then noticed all the CCTV screens and realized that [[Bushmaster]] had arrived into their club and was fighting his way through their security guards with ease, before managing to subdue Cage, as Bushmaster continued making his way to their safe room. Stokes witnessed Bushmaster pound on their steel door, denting it, while Shades demanded she gives him the gun so he could attempt to kill Bushmaster, which she reluctantly agreed to.
[[File:MDillard-WhereTheHellIsLukeCage.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes wondering where [[Luke Cage]] is now]]
Stokes furiously questioned where Cage was, until Bushmaster was able to break down their door before Shades fired a shot at his eye, which had barely missed Bushmaster. Having avoided the gunshot, Bushmaster pushed Shades backwards, causing him to crash into Stokes, before Cage and [[Misty Knight]] stormed in the room and had tackled Bushmaster. However, Bushmaster was soon able to subdue Cage and Knight, with only Shades now standing between him and Stokes, who was quickly knocked down. However, when Bushmaster tried to grab Stokes, Cage then returned and knocked him back.
[[File:BushmasterAlmostKillingMDillard.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is held in [[Bushmaster]]'s deadly grasp]]
Stokes had then witnessed Bushmaster defeating both Shades and Cage, as she then attempted to run for the exit, only for Bushmaster to drag her onto her feet, while she cursed and demanded that he let her go. Ignoring her, Bushmaster demanded that she look him in the eyes while he crushed her skull, only for Knight to use her [[Misty Knight's Prosthetic Arm|Prosthetic Arm]] to knock Bushmaster back, before he was able to subdue her, allowing Cage to get back onto his feet and then repeatedly punch Bushmaster with considerable force, striking him under the chin with such power that Bushmaster was taken completely off his feet.
[[File:MDillard-BreakHisGodDamnNeck.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes orders [[Luke Cage]] to kill [[Bushmaster]]]]
With Bushmaster now bloody and dazed, Cage was able to drag him onto his feet as he put him into a chock-hold, which Bushmaster was unable to break free from, no matter how many times he then tried to strike back against Cage's grip. Witnessing this, Stokes then furiously screamed at Cage to break Bushmaster's neck, and kill him for her. However, despite having Bushmaster at his mercy, Cage had listened to Knight's reasoning and finally let Bushmaster go. Despite failing to kill her, Stokes then witnessed the defeated Bushmaster running from the scene, unable to continue his fight against Stokes' protectors.
[[File:MDillard-YouAreUnderArrest.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes finally being placed under arrest]]
Stokes then followed Cage back upstairs into her office, where Cage confirmed with [[Priscilla Ridley]] that Bushmaster was gone. However, while Stokes was pouring herself a drink to calm her nerves, she had then witnessed Shades handing her revolver over to Knight, which was the evidence Knight needed to link her to the deaths of [[Candace Miller]] and [[Cottonmouth]], as well as the [[Massacre at Gwen's|Massacre]] at ''[[Gwen's]]''. Stokes then listened as Knight put her under arrest for these murders, as she read Stokes her rights, while she had continued to claim that she had not been the one who had actually pulled the trigger of the gun.
[[File:MDillardRantingAtPoliceWhileHandcuffed.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes makes her rant while being arrested]]
However, Stokes had remained confident, noting that it would only be Shades' word against hers, as she called Shades the gutter gangster and lowlife, while she had referred to herself as Mariah Stokes, and noted her credits as a councilwoman for [[Harlem]], as well as being a millionaire philanthropist, while accusing the police of trying to drag a successful black woman's name through the mud. However, while Stokes remained confident that their courts of public opinion would clear her, Ridley took her into custody and insisted that the court of law would convict her, while Cage and Knight watched on.{{Ref|LC212}}

====Sentenced to Prison====
[[File:BenDonovanCourtRoomDebate2.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes attends her trail for her many crimes]]
{{Quote|The water has gotten hotter, what should've been a thunderstorm is now becoming a hurricane, but no one's prepared, nothing has been fortified, resources will be overwhelmed. The rains will come torrential and the water will rise too fast, people won't have time to evacuate. If you release me, I will fortify that wall around [[Harlem]].|Mariah Stokes to [[Amanda Garmon]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Following her arrest by the [[New York City Police Department]], Stokes was brought to the [[New York State Supreme Court Building|Supreme Court Building]], to be put on trial for her many crimes. Stokes sat in silence, while [[Blake Tower]] accused her of twelve counts of murder in the first degree, noting that among her victims, was her own cousin, [[Cottonmouth]], although [[Benjamin Donovan]] had stood up to object to Tower's grandstanding, insisting that this should actually be a simple case for the first time offender.
[[File:BlackMariahInCourt.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes looking around the courtroom]]
However, Tower insisted that Stokes' hands were drenched in blood, noting her involvement in the [[Massacre at Gwen's|massacre]] at [[Gwen's]], as well as several SEC charges based on her illegal dealings with [[Atreus Plastics]]. While Tower continued describing these charges against her, Stokes looked to the back of their courtroom, where she saw [[Misty Knight]] and [[Luke Cage]] were watching her, before seeing [[Rosalie Carbone]] entering the courtroom. However, while Donovan continued to defend Stokes, the case was interrupted when several [[Jamaica]]ns stood up and furiously accused her of murder, resulting with them all being dragged away.
[[File:BlackMariahAsksToGiveASpeech-Court.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes giving a speech to the courtroom]]
Once the Jamaicans were removed, Judge [[Amanda Garmon]] denied Stokes' bail, ordering her passport be revoked, and she would then be sent to [[Rikers Island]] until her trial date was set. However, before Garmon could complete the sentence, Stokes requested a chance to speak, which Garmon granted, which caused [[Tilda Johnson]] to walk out. Standing up, Stokes had insisted that she was not a flight risk, or a risk to the people, insisting that she really loved her people. Stokes then went on to explain that there was a wall around [[Harlem]] that had been build by [[Buggy Stokes]] and [[Mama Mabel]], which was eroding.
[[File:BlackMariah-GodHelpHarlem.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes warns everyone of a wave of crime]]
Stokes compared the situation in Harlem to {{WPS|Global Warming}}, insisting that the water was getting hotter and they had all been ignoring the dangers, promising that they were not prepared and their resources would soon be overwhelmed. Making it clear that the [[War for Harlem]] would continue, Stokes insisted she would be able to fortify Harlem if released, although Garmon was offended by Stokes' comparisons to the {{WPS|Hurricane Katrina}}. Stokes went on to insist that the [[Stokes Crime Family]] had protected Harlem, promising they would all regret putting her in prison, although Garmon had ignored Stokes' warnings.{{Ref|LC213}}

====[[Attack on Mariah Stokes|Attacked by Assassins]]====
[[File:BlackMariah&MooreWalkingInAHallway.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is escorted out of her jail cell room]]
{{Quote|Thanks for keeping my back."<br>"Don't thank me yet, bitch. [[Mama Mabel|Mabel]] didn't do right by me."<br>"That's my fault?"<br>"We'll protect you, but you're gonna have to pay us."<br>"You know I'm good, I am good for it. Just one condition, I wanna carve my name in that Jamaican bitch!|Mariah Stokes and [[Kalinda Potter]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Having been sent into [[Rikers Island]], Stokes was let out of her cell by Officer [[Moore (Department of Correction)|Moore]], and led through the prison's hallways, with neither of them saying a word. However, before they could reach their destination, the pair were cornered by two female inmates, who managed to hold down Moore and repeatedly stabbed her, while Stokes then desperately attempted to make her escape, only to find that all of the hallway doors inside of the prison had remained locked, as she was cornered with the two female inmates.
[[File:BlackMariahDrenchedInAerosol.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is almost killed by other prisoners]]
One of the inmates revealed themselves to be [[Jamaica]]n, as they had proceeded to pour gasoline all over Stokes, before the other revealed that she was working for [[Rosalie Carbone]], who had ordered Stokes' assassination. However, just as Carbone's assassin lit the match and prepared to [[Attack on Mariah Stokes|burn]] Stokes alive, two other inmates then appeared and slit their throats, in front of the horrified Stokes. She was then greeted by another inmate, who questioned if Stokes could actually remember who she was, as Stokes remembered her as Sunflower, although the inmate revealed she actually used the name [[Kalinda Potter]] now.
[[File:BlackMariahMeetsKalinda.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes thanks [[Kalinda Potter]] for saving her]]
Potter then noted that [[Mama Mabel]] would have been proud of what Stokes had become, although it was a shame that she was in Rykers. When Stokes thanked Potter for saving her life, Potter noted that she should not thank her yet, making it clear that she had no love for the [[Stokes Crime Family]] as Mabel had previously betrayed her, as Potter promised to protect Stokes, as she as she agreed to pay them for the service. Stokes seemingly agreed to Potter's terms, while noting that she would be good for the money, but made her request to carve her name into the face of the Jamaican prisoner who had attacked her.
[[File:BlackMariah-LookAtMyEyes.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes tells the assassins she is in charge]]
Stokes had then requested a blade to use on the Jamaican prisoner's face, which Potter agreed to. However, as soon as Stokes was given their blade, she then used it to slice open Potter's throat, leaving her to bleed to death, as Stokes noted that she used to be one of [[Pistol Pete]]'s women. Stokes then addressed Potter's henchwomen, telling them that she was now in charge of their entire prison, in the wake of Potter's death, promising to pay them a hundred and fifty thousand dollars to work for her, as well as twenty thousand each for just that night, while she would also be paying their people on the outside.
[[File:BlackMariahCallsDonovanInPrison.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes calling [[Benjamin Donovan|Ben Donovan]] over the phone]]
Stokes told the henchwomen to ask about her reputation, to confirm that she was not to be messed with, which the henchwomen agreed to, as Stokes ordered them to clean up the corpses of Potter and the other two women who had attacked her. Having gained some power already, Stokes then went over to the corpse of Moore and stole her phone, as she used it to call [[Benjamin Donovan]], demanding that he come to Rikers Island and bring the forty thousand that Stokes now needed to pay for Potter's henchwomen, as she ignored Donovan's objections and demanded that he do what she asked of him.{{Ref|LC213}}

====Removing Any Dangers====
[[File:BenDonovan-DillardPrisonMeeting.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes meeting with [[Benjamin Donovan|Ben Donovan]] in [[Rikers Island|prison]]]]
{{Quote|It's dangerous, it's risky, but it's worth it. Anybody else roll?"<br>"No."<br>"Can't give them the chance to."<br>"Everyone?"<br>"Everyone not protected by blood or attorney-client privilege."<br>"I appreciate that.|Mariah Stokes and [[Benjamin Donovan]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Stokes arranged a meeting with [[Benjamin Donovan]], as he confirmed that they could speak truthfully inside there without any risk of being overheard as it would be illegal for anyone to listen in, noting that he had bribed the CO and ensured that all their monitors were turned off. Stokes had first asked about dealing with [[Shades]], although Donovan explained that he was now untouchable, much to Stokes' great frustration, as regardless, Shades had already gone onto the record, so it would be too late to stop him.
[[File:MDillard-DonovanPrisonMeeting1.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes discusses how to get [[Shades]] killed]]
However, Stokes suggested that they could focus more on the juries, claiming that they could build a narrative around the widow who had been seduced by an aggressive gangster-like Shades, who led her to the life of crime against her will through seduction, as Donovan noted how Shades had already confessed to numerous murders, which had included [[Candace Miller]] and [[Comanche]], while their [[Stokes' Revolver]] was used as evidence against Stokes was her family heirloom, which Shades had stolen from her. Donovan then noted how they could use Shades' actions after [[Cottonmouth]]'s murder to their advantage.
[[File:MDillard-DonovanPrisonMeeting2.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes giving orders to [[Benjamin Donovan]]]]
Stokes then ordered Donovan to put out a hit against Shades, before questioning if their former allies had flipped, telling Donovan to have them killed before they could consider doing it. Donovan confirmed she meant everyone, including [[Alex Wesley]], as Stokes noted that this would be everyone who was not protected by blood while promising that Donovan would still be kept alive for all of his legal work, much to his relief, as well as [[Sugar]] for giving Stokes his wife's clothes after her [[Mariah Dillard's Brownstone|brownstone]] was [[Rescue of Mariah Dillard|destroyed]]. Donovan did as ordered, resulting in seven of Stokes' henchmen being killed, as well as Wesley.{{Ref|LC213}}

====Visited by Shades====
[[File:ShadesVisitingMDillardInPrison.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes meeting with [[Shades]] in the prison]]
{{Quote|Don't leave... I already had to off [[Kalinda Potter|somebody]] in [[Rikers Island|here]], I'm gonna have to do it again."<br>"Let me give you some advice, gangster to a gangster. This is your life now, your head on a swivel, no one you can ever trust. Don't worry, you're a natural.|Mariah Stokes and [[Shades]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Despite many of their former allies getting assassinated, [[Shades]] had managed to survive Stokes' order, as he came into [[Rikers Island]] to confront her. Once they were alone, Shades mockingly told her that there was nothing that she could do to him; however, he noted that there was a lot that he could do to her. Stokes told Shades that she had been hurt, when he became a snitch for the [[New York City Police Department]], questioning if Shades had ever really loved her.
[[File:MDillard-FinalShadesTalk.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes listens to [[Shades]] and his devotion]]
While Shades claimed that he still loved her, Stokes had then asked if he loved [[Comanche]] more, to which Shades then told Stokes that she had never understood how getting sent into [[Seagate Penitentiary]] felt real until being set free. Shades insisted that he had been devoted to Stokes, which Comanche would have eventually understood, allowing him and Stokes to control [[Harlem]] together. Shades noted how Stokes how spoken with him about being a good person while moving away from the life of the gangster; however, it was Stokes who had sold her soul for the legacy of the [[Stokes Crime Family]] which she hated.
[[File:MDillardToShades-FinalGoodbye.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes being given advice from [[Shades]]]]
Shades then reminded Stokes that could have simply sold [[Harlem's Paradise]] to him or sold her {{WPS|Jean-Michel Basquiat}} painting, and none of this would have happened. As Shades got up to leave, Stokes had begged him to stay, while noting that she had already been forced to murder [[Kalinda Potter]] and was afraid she would have to do it again. Shades gave Stokes some advice, telling her that this came from one gangster to another, that she would spend the rest of her life looking over her shoulder. Shades told Stokes that she was a natural with the life before he finally walked away, ignoring all of Stokes' pleas.
[[File:MDillardUpset-TildaAnnouncement.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is informed of [[Tilda Johnson]]'s visit]]
Since Shades ignored her pleas for him to stay, Stokes was left alone in their room, before she was then rejoined by [[Benjamin Donovan]], as he informed her that [[Tilda Johnson]] had just been in contact with him, and she was ready to come and visit Stokes in their prison. However, Stokes remained too devastated by Shades' walking away from her to fully acknowledge what Donovan was saying, as she had told him to bring Johnson to her so that they could have their reunion and get it over with. Following this, Stokes buried her head in her hands, as she wept for Shades, as well as everything else that she had lost.{{Ref|LC213}}

====Tilda Johnson's Goodbye====
[[File:BlackMariahTJohnson-PrisonMeeting.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is visited by [[Tilda Johnson]] in [[Rikers Island|prison]]]]
{{Quote|When I get out, you and I, we will start over again from scratch. Now, you need to forgive me. My time [[Rikers Island|here]] already, I have changed in ways that I never anticipated."<br>"Your life is a waste, every person who has ever loved you, who you didn't kill, you pushed away, even your precious Harlem.|Mariah Stokes and [[Tilda Johnson]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Stokes was later visited in [[Rikers Island]] by [[Tilda Johnson]], as Stokes told Johnson that it was good to see her, before acknowledging that she had said some harsh words the last time they had seen each other. Stokes then questioned if Johnson had ever been raped, telling her that when she was raped by [[Pistol Pete]], a part of her had died to cope with it. Stokes had acknowledged that she knew she should love Johnson but claimed that she did not know how.
[[File:BlackMariahInRykers.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes is questioned on killing [[Alex Wesley]]]]
When Stokes tried to find the right words, Johnson suggested that she should try saying nothing at all. When Johnson called her evil, Stokes insisted that she was actually necessary. However, Johnson had questioned if it had been necessary for her to murder all of her former allies, including [[Alex Wesley]]. Johnson then questioned if Stokes actually believed that any of this was going to work in Stokes' favor and that she could still get out of prison, to which Stokes insisted that if one jury member was from [[Harlem]], then she would be a chance to walk free from her trial.
[[File:BlackMariahMakesTruceToTJohnson.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes tries to amend with [[Tilda Johnson]]]]
Stokes insisted that if it were the case, nobody would be able to contradict what the jury member from Harlem had to say, claiming that this was black excellence shielding her. Stokes promised Johnson that, once she was freed, the two of them would start up their relationship over again, telling Johnson that she needed to forgive her. Stokes claimed that her time in Rikers had already changed her, only for Johnson to claim that her life had been a waste, noting that every person who had ever loved Stokes, had been pushed away or murdered, as she mockingly claimed that Stokes had even pushed away Harlem.
[[File:BlackMariah-INoLongerSeePete'sFace.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes gives [[Tilda Johnson]] her blessings]]
Stokes claimed that she pushed Johnson away, like [[Mama Mabel]] did to her, and this had made Johnson stronger since nobody could hurt Johnson, as she would never be hurt more than this, as Johnson had questioned if it was a blessing, to which Stokes insisted that she was prepared for the world. Stokes insisted that nobody would be able to betray Johnson, as she would never allow them to get close enough. Stokes then told Johnson to watch over [[Harlem's Paradise]] for her, as she claimed that the club was home, and that their music lived inside of Johnson, whether she had surrendered to it or not.
[[File:Tilda kisses her mom.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes being loved again by [[Tilda Johnson]]]]
Stokes told Johnson that, before she walked away from the club and the legacy of the [[Stokes Crime Family]], she should first stand inside the Paradise and feel the power that the club held. Stokes then told Johnson that she no longer saw Pete's face when she looked at her, as she only saw her own face. With that, Johnson stood up and told Stokes that she loved her, before then softly kissing Stokes on the lips and claiming that she hoped that she found her peace in some form, although she did not actually believe that Stokes deserved any of it before Johnson walked out of Rikers Island
[[File:BlackMariahRealizesThatTJohnsonLied.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes realizing [[Tilda Johnson]] lied to her]]
Once Johnson had walked out from Rikers Island, Stokes was then joined by [[Benjamin Donovan]], who noted that Stokes would never be able to guess who had just called him. However, Stokes had become distracted by the way Johnson had walked out, as she told Donovan that Johnson had called her "mother" and not "mommy" as she had usually done. Stokes then laughed about this, before telling Donovan that she did not believe anything that Johnson had said to her. Stokes had then told Donovan to do something officially for her, before being told that [[Luke Cage]] had called, as he wanted to meet with her.{{Ref|LC213}}

====Last Will and Testament====
[[File:BlackMariahDeclaresWhoIsInHerWill.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes makes a will with [[Benjamin Donovan]]]]
{{Quote|This [[Harlem's Paradise|club]] will be [[Luke Cage|his]] siren. He will be lulled by its song, lulled by so-called greatness. The [[James Lucas|preacher]]'s son will think he can use the roost to change things, to control it. But in the end, it will change him.|Mariah Stokes to [[Benjamin Donovan]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Following her meeting with [[Tilda Johnson]], Stokes immediately arranged a private meeting with [[Benjamin Donovan]], as she informed him of her intention to write out her new official last will and testament. She declared that the {{WPS|Jean-Michel Basquiat}} painting would be given to the {{WPS|Studio Museum in Harlem}} and her remaining millions would go to the [[Family First Initiative]]. Stokes had also noted that she intended to only leave [[Cottonmouth]]'s keyboard to Johnson, while she now intended to leave the control of [[Harlem's Paradise]] to [[Luke Cage]] instead of Johnson.
[[File:BlackMariahGivesLCageHarlem'sParadise.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes deciding to give [[Luke Cage]] her [[Harlem's Paradise|club]]]]
Donovan questioned this decision, asking if it was because Johnson had just lied to her, which Stokes denied. Stokes explained her belief that Harlem's Paradise was the crown jewel of [[Harlem]], and it should therefore only be given to somebody who truly loved Harlem just as much as she did. Stokes compared her decision to the legend of the sirens, as she believed that the club would be a siren for Cage, and convince him that he had would have the power to change Harlem for the better, while Stokes believed that having control over these crime organizations of [[New York City]] would eventually change and forever corrupt Cage.{{Ref|LC213}}

====Death by Poison====
[[File:BDonovanMDillard-VisitedByLCage.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes gets a surprise visit from [[Luke Cage]]]]
{{Quote|You can save me?"<br>"Nah, I've done all the saving I can do, but I will keep you company."<br>"I can't... It burns..."<br>"Good."<br>"We ain't done yet.|Mariah Stokes and [[Luke Cage]]|They Reminisce Over You (T.R.O.Y.)}}
Having changed her last will and testament, Stokes then invited [[Luke Cage]] to see her in [[Rikers Island]], as he had requested. Once Cage had arrived, [[Benjamin Donovan]] noted that the situation was unusual and admittedly, extremely awkward for all of them, to which Cage then simply invited him to leave, much to the amusement of Stokes. Once Donovan had left the room, Stokes noted that this was the first time that she and Cage had both wanted to see each other.
[[File:BlackMariahInsultsLCageInPrison.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes insults [[Luke Cage]] in the visitor room]]
Cage then informed Stokes that he had met with [[Rosalie Carbone]], to which Stokes noted that she had heard about this. Cage further explained that he had managed to repair all the walls around [[Harlem]] before the violence got worse, causing Stokes to question if Cage had become the newest gangster in Harlem, although Cage clarified that he was more of a sheriff. When Stokes had questioned whether he should be called a warden, Cage simply retorted that she was the one locked up in a prison. Cage proceeded to remind Stokes that [[Shades]], and the [[Stylers]] were gone, as he requested that Stokes not undo the peace by killing more people.
[[File:BlackMariah-MadeMeFindWhoIReallyAm.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes tells [[Luke Cage]] he is the catalyst]]
However, Stokes denied having the power to kill anybody, suggesting that Cage had thought too highly of her, although Cage insisted that he thought very little of her, making it clear that he had no plans of thinking about her ever again. Stokes had then noted that everyone else who had come into Rikers to see her had been invited, while Cage had come on his own, prompting Stokes to question if he really cared about her. Cage accused her of being delusional for this reasoning, but Stokes called him the catalyst that had made her into the person she was now, claiming that they were actually responsible for each other.
[[File:BlackMariah-Harlem'sGonnaNeedAKing.jpg|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes mockingly compliments [[Luke Cage]]]]
While Cage scoffed at all these suggestions, he called Stokes a bitch, before insisting that no offence should be taken, while Stokes claimed to not be offended, before calling Cage a n***a. As the pair shared a brief chuckle over their insults to each other, Stokes noted how Cage was clearly the son of a preacher, like [[James Lucas]], noting that even while he was being ugly, he was still regal. Stokes then told Cage that Harlem would need a King now that she was locked up in prison, and said she was glad that it was going to be Cage, while Cage had retorted that he was glad that Stokes would never get out of prison.
[[File:MDillardSpittingOutBlood.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes realizes she is dying from the poison]]
As Cage noted that everybody had already walked away from Stokes, and he intended to be the last one to do so, Stokes then insisted that Cage should not be too sure about that. However, in the moment Stokes was speaking, she had unexpectedly spat out some blood, as a horrified Stokes stared in shock and disgust at her blood on their table, making Cage confused about what was happening to her. Stokes had then realized that [[Tilda Johnson]] had managed to [[Murder of Mariah Stokes|poison]] her, using a special form of a [[Beso de la Araña|lipstick]], which Johnson had used to kiss her from their last meeting, as Stokes then collapsed onto the floor.
[[File:Cage watching Mariah die.png|{{AltFloat}}|Stokes dies painfully in [[Luke Cage]]'s arms]]
Cage then ran to Stokes' aid, as he held her in his arms while Stokes began choking on her own blood. When Cage noted that none of the prison guards were coming to her aid, due to the cameras being turned off, Stokes questioned if he could rescue her, although Cage admitted that he could not, as he had already done all the saving he could. As she died, Stokes noted that the poison was burning her up from the inside, with Cage making it clear that he was glad that her death was painful. With her final breaths, Stokes had then told Cage that they were not done yet before she had died in his arms.{{Ref|LC213}}

